# ROV Project – Cursor Guidelines

## General Rules
- The project has two main modules: backend (Go) and UI (React/TypeScript + Three.js simulator).
- Cursor must place generated code into the correct directory based on the project structure.
- All physics, motor logic, telemetry, and protocol logic belong in Go.
- All UI components, HUD, WebSocket client, and WebGL simulation belong in the React UI under `/ui/src/sim/`.
- Do not use Unity or any external 3D engine outside the browser.

## Backend (Go)
- All backend code goes under `/backend`.
- Executable entrypoints go under `/backend/cmd/<name>/main.go`.
- Internal logic goes under `/backend/internal/...`.
- Shared libraries go under `/backend/pkg/...`.
- Mock mode: `MOCK_MODE=1` (default) enables internal physics; `MOCK_MODE=0` for real hardware.

## UI (React/TypeScript + Three.js)
- All UI code goes under `/ui`.
- WebGL simulator lives under `/ui/src/sim/`.
- Nose camera must be attached to the ROV front (first-person); no external follow camera.
- When the user requests video feed, 3D environment, ROV movement, or camera logic → generate code under `/ui/src/sim/...`.

## Protocol
- All protocol documentation goes under `/protocol`.
- WebSocket messages follow JSON structures in `/protocol/commands.md` and `/protocol/telemetry.md`.
- UI → backend: control commands.
- Backend → UI: telemetry updates (includes echoed command).

## Modes: Simulation vs Real ROV
- **simulation**: WebGL simulator in browser + backend mock physics (`MOCK_MODE=1`).
- **real**: backend controls real motors (`MOCK_MODE=0`); UI protocol unchanged.

## Architecture Principles
- Backend is the “brain”.
- WebGL simulator in the UI is the “eyes” in simulation mode.
- React UI is the “control panel”.
- Code must remain modular for real hardware integration.
